05582nam a22009735i 9781501511929DE-B159720230127011820.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230127t20202020gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2019954491  a97815015119297 a10.1515/97815015119292doi  a(DE-B1597)507150  a(OCoLC)1143836239  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE00aP53.43b.T77 2020 7aLAN0090002bisacsh1 aTsakona, Villy, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRecontextualizing Humor :bRethinking the Analysis and Teaching of Humor /cVilly Tsakona. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (XVI, 229 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLanguage Play and Creativity ,x2363-7749 ;v400tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgments -- tContents -- tList of Tables -- tList of Figures -- tTranscription conventions for the Greek oral data and its translation -- tIntroduction -- t1. Context in humor research -- t2. Humor and metapragmatics -- t3. Genres with/and humor -- t4. Towards a “contextualized” theory of humor -- t5. Teaching about humor within a critical literacy framework -- t6. Conclusions -- tReferences -- tSubject Index -- tAuthor Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHumor may surface in numerous and diverse contexts, which at the same time determine how humor works, its form, and its functions and consequences for interlocutors. Adopting a sociolinguistic and discourse analytic perspective, this study is aligned with approaches to humor exploring the variety of humorous genres, the wide range of sociopragmatic functions of humor, and the more or less dissimilar perceptions speakers may have concerning what humor is, what it means, and how it works. The chapters of this book propose a new theoretical approach to the analysis of humor by bringing context into focus. Furthermore, the study explores how we can teach about humor within a critical literacy framework creating classroom space for everyday humorous texts that are part of students’ social realities, and simultaneously taking into account that humor may yield multiple, disparaging, and often conflicting interpretations. This book is intended to appeal to humor researchers from various disciplines (such as linguistics, media studies, cultural studies, literary studies, sociology, anthropology, folklore) as well as to professionals or researchers in education.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aHumor. 4aHumor. 4aMetapragmatik. 4aSchriftlichkeit. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aCritical Literacy.  aHumor.  aHumorous Genres.  aMetapragmatics.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Ebook Package English 2020z978311069628808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2020 Part 1z978311069627108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDe Gruyter English eBooks 2020 - UCz978311065906108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDe Gruyter Mouton Frontlist 2020z978311074316608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Linguistics 2020 Englishz978311070476108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Linguistics 2020z9783110704563oZDB-23-DSP0 cEPUBz97815015115230 cprintz978150151748840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150151192940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501511929423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501511929/original  a978-3-11-065906-1  De Gruyter English eBook